cmnh1skaq009vk9089qe3lhzr	cmnh1sk3c003tk908gigp09oy	Low digital literacy among some MSME owners/staff may slow adoption of digital tools and basic automation.	Low digital literacy among some MSME owners/staff may slow adoption of digital tools and basic automation.	MEDIUM	Delays or incomplete adoption of digital tools and automation.	Use step-by-step, practice-based training; adopt very simple interfaces; identify one “focal person” per MSME to support peers; maintain paper-based backup procedures during the transition period.	open	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122
cmnh1skaq009wk908aq4j7szh	cmnh1sk3c003tk908gigp09oy	Delays in procurement or installation of equipment could postpone maquila start-up.	Delays in procurement or installation of equipment could postpone maquila start-up.	MEDIUM	Postponement of maquila start-up and related activities.	Include time buffers in the implementation schedule; prioritize locally available equipment and suppliers; plan installation in phases so that partial operation can start even if some components are delayed.	open	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122
cmnh1skaq009xk908p8thyv59	cmnh1sk3c003tk908gigp09oy	Underutilization of the maquila if biomass supply or demand for new products is lower than expected.	Underutilization of the maquila if biomass supply or demand for new products is lower than expected.	MEDIUM	Reduced impact and sustainability of the maquila.	Validate demand and supply conditions during the design phase; diversify processed products (not only coffee by-products but also other local agro-food products); establish written agreements on minimum usage commitments with participating MSMEs.	open	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122
cmnh1skaq009yk908qn3xv2ak	cmnh1sk3c003tk908gigp09oy	Coordination challenges among the cooperative and multiple MSMEs may slow decision-making and implementation.	Coordination challenges among the cooperative and multiple MSMEs may slow decision-making and implementation.	MEDIUM	Slowed decision-making and implementation.	Define a simple governance structure and roles from the outset; appoint a dedicated project coordinator; schedule regular coordination meetings; document agreements and procedures in writing to reduce misunderstandings.	open	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122
cmnh1skaq009zk908m5zjzs99	cmnh1sk3c003tk908gigp09oy	Long-term sustainability of digital and monitoring systems after the end of the project.	Long-term sustainability of digital and monitoring systems after the end of the project.	MEDIUM	Risk of systems not being maintained or used after project ends.	Use open-source and low-cost tools; train local staff in basic maintenance and troubleshooting; document systems in clear language; select components that can be easily replaced locally. The involvement of local private sector actors (such as Nuevo Kaffeetal) and national technical institutions (such as the Inter-American Institute for Cooperation on Agriculture – IICA) helps ensure local presence, continuity, and trust beyond the life of the project.	open	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122
cmnh1skaq00a0k908hhl3qw5m	cmnh1sk3c003tk908gigp09oy	Governance and costsharing model. Lack of consensus on governance and cost-sharing model may lead to conflict or misunderstandings.	Governance and costsharing model. Lack of consensus on governance and cost-sharing model may lead to conflict or misunderstandings.	MEDIUM	Conflict or misunderstandings among participants.	To proactively address this risk, the governance and cost-sharing model will be built through a fully participatory process embedded in three key project activities. In A4.1, the governance structures, roles, and responsibilities of the commercialization network will be collectively designed and formally agreed upon by all participants, ensuring that no structure is imposed externally. In A4.2, product specifications, quality criteria, and packaging requirements will be developed jointly, creating shared ownership over the standards that all members must meet. Finally, in A4.5, the commercialization mechanism itself will be co-designed and tested through a pilot phase, allowing participants to identify and resolve operational disagreements before full implementation. This participatory approach ensures that all decisions reflect the collective voice of the network, reducing the risk of conflict and increasing long-term commitment.	open	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122	2026-04-02 05:42:21.122
